    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2012/03/big-lagoon-small-lagoon-miniloc-island-el-nido-palawan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'El Nido Tour A: A Calm Read on Big Lagoon and the Miniloc Loop',
        'slug' => 'el-nido-tour-a-big-lagoon-miniloc-loop',
        'excerpt' => 'Tour A is still the El Nido island day most first-timers default to. Here is what the route looks like now, what to bring, and how to time the Big Lagoon kayak so the photos still work.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Tour A in El Nido is the loop everyone knows by name. It used to bundle Big Lagoon and Small Lagoon together, but since late 2018 the Small Lagoon got moved to Tour D to ease the crowding around Miniloc Island. The current Tour A is Big Lagoon, Hidden Lagoon, Simizu Island or Payong-Payong, and Seven Commandos Beach for the closing stretch.</p><p>The route still earns the hype, but only if you plan for the lagoon fees, the kayak wait, and the boat queue. Tara, here is the practical kwento for a first-timer.</p><h2>What the Day Actually Looks Like</h2><p>Boats leave the El Nido town beach by around 9 a.m. after a quick orientation at the tourism office. You will pay an environmental development fee on top of the tour cost, valid for ten days, and a separate Big Lagoon entrance that the boat crew collects in cash.</p><h3>Big Lagoon and Hidden Lagoon</h3><p>Big Lagoon is the headline stop. The boat anchors at the entrance and you transfer to a kayak or wade in if the tide allows. The limestone walls funnel the water into that shallow turquoise color the feed photos use. Go in early to beat the kayak queue from the other boats. Hidden Lagoon is a short paddle away and the entrance opens only at low tide, so the order depends on the schedule that day.</p><h3>Simizu Island Lunch</h3><p>Simizu or Payong-Payong is the lunch stop. Crews set up grilled fish, pork, eggplant, and rice on long shared tables. Eat under the trees because there is no real shade once the sun is overhead. Sometimes the boat reroutes to Pinagbuyutan if Simizu is full, which is the better island in my opinion.</p><h3>Seven Commandos for the Finish</h3><p>Seven Commandos Beach closes the day. It has the rare combination of a long white sand stretch and bar service. Order halo-halo or a cold buko, then sit out the last hour before the boats head back to El Nido at golden hour.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, no spray cans, no nano particles</li><li>Aqua shoes with grip for rocky beach landings</li><li>A dry bag for your phone, camera, and the cash for fees</li><li>A light rashguard, the sun out on the bay is no joke</li><li>A reusable water bottle, the boat crew refills</li></ul><h2>What to Skip</h2><p>Skip the flotation belts the vendors push at the lagoon entrance if you can swim. They jam up the kayak channels and you do not really need them inside Big Lagoon. Skip the GoPro stick attachments that hover over the limestone walls, the rangers will call you out.</p><h2>Getting In and Around</h2><p>The fastest way to El Nido is to fly into Lio Airport from Manila on <a href="https://www.airswift.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">AirSWIFT</a>, the small carrier that runs the route. The cheaper way is to fly into Puerto Princesa on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and take a six-hour van north along the new road. The van trip is sulit if you are not in a rush and want to see the Palawan interior.</p><h3>Where to Stay</h3><p>Stay in El Nido town if you want walkable food and easy boat access. Stay in Corong-Corong if you want quieter sunsets and a short tricycle ride to the pier. For listings you can cross-check on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g469393-El_Nido_Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h2>One More Tip</h2><p>Book Tour A on a weekday if you can. The Saturday boats are noticeably more crowded and the Big Lagoon kayak queue can eat a full hour out of your morning. Mid-week also gives you a calmer Seven Commandos at the end.</p><p>El Nido still does the job for first-timers. The Tour A loop is busy by design, but the route holds up if you treat it as a slow boat day instead of a checklist.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2012/03/big-lagoon-small-lagoon-miniloc-island-el-nido-palawan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'El Nido Tour A Guide: Big Lagoon and Miniloc | Resort Guru PH',
