    [
        'source_url' => 'https://graphicwanderlust.com/2025/03/10/el-nido-palawan-travel-guide-itinerary/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Graphic Wanderlust',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Nacpan and Duli: The Two El Nido Beaches Worth the Scooter Ride',
        'slug' => 'nacpan-duli-el-nido-beaches-scooter-ride',
        'excerpt' => 'Nacpan is the long golden stretch most travelers ride out for. Duli is the quieter neighbor with surf. Here is how to do both in one slow day from El Nido town.',
        'content_html' => '<p>El Nido is mostly known for the island-hopping tours, but the mainland beaches up north hold their own day. Nacpan is the four-kilometer golden stretch lined with palms, and Duli is the quieter surf beach about an hour further from town. Together they make a calm second-day plan when you want to skip the boats and just sit on sand.</p><p>This is not a tour you book, it is a ride you take. A scooter rental from El Nido town puts both beaches within reach, but only if you start early and respect the road conditions.</p><h2>Renting the Scooter</h2><p>Most guesthouses in El Nido town can arrange a scooter rental, and the standard day rate covers the bike, a basic helmet, and a small lock. Fill up at the gas station near the main road before you leave town, the small roadside refills along the way are more expensive and the petrol quality is hit or miss.</p><h3>Road Conditions</h3><p>The road to Nacpan is mostly paved with a short rough stretch near the village. Duli requires you to push another 45 minutes north on a quieter road with more pothole sections. Ride slow, wear the helmet even when no one is checking, and do not ride after sunset because there are no streetlights and the village dogs lie on the asphalt for the leftover warmth.</p><h2>Nacpan First</h2><p>Get to Nacpan by 9 a.m. and you will have the long stretch mostly to yourself before the van tours arrive. Park at the village entrance, pay the small environmental fee, and walk to the south end first because the sand there is cleaner and the palm shade is real. Pawikan snorkeling spot at the northern end has shallow reefs and the occasional sea turtle if you swim out.</p><h3>Lunch on the Beach</h3><p>The simple cantinas along the Nacpan beach line serve grilled fish, sinigang, and cold buko. Eat under the bamboo shade, then nap for an hour before the ride to Duli. Mad Monkey Hostel up on the cliff has a longer menu if you want a sit-down lunch with a view of the full bay.</p><h2>Duli for the Quiet Afternoon</h2><p>Duli is the trade-off beach. The drive is longer and the road is rougher, but the beach is mostly empty even on weekends. From November to March, the surf picks up and a few small surf camps run lessons on the smaller break.</p><h3>What Duli Has</h3><ul><li>A long undeveloped sand stretch facing the open sea</li><li>Two or three light-material cantinas for grilled lunch</li><li>A small tourism office where you register before entering</li><li>Free scooter parking near the entrance</li><li>Soft afternoon light for sunset photos with no crowd</li></ul><p>Bring your own water and snacks because the cantinas close early. There is no nightlife, no signal, just the open sea and the wind through the palms.</p><h2>Getting Back to Town</h2><p>Leave Duli by 4 p.m. so you reach El Nido town before sunset. The ride back feels longer because the sun is lower, and the same potholes you dodged in the morning are harder to spot in the afternoon shadow. Refuel at the same gas station before you return the bike.</p><h2>Getting to El Nido</h2><p>If you have not booked the trip yet, the fastest route is the direct flight from Manila on <a href="https://www.airswift.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">AirSWIFT</a>. The more affordable route is to fly into Puerto Princesa on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and take a van north. For places to sleep near both Nacpan and El Nido town, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g469393-El_Nido_Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><p>Two beaches, one scooter, one slow day. This is the El Nido itinerary that survives the second visit.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://graphicwanderlust.com/2025/03/10/el-nido-palawan-travel-guide-itinerary/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Graphic Wanderlust</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Nacpan and Duli Beach Guide El Nido | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm one-day plan for Nacpan and Duli beaches outside El Nido. Scooter route, lunch stops, road conditions, and what to bring for the quieter afternoon.',
        'tags' => 'El Nido, Nacpan, Duli, Palawan, beaches',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'el-nido',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2017/08/puerto-princesa-palawan-travel-guide-itinerary-blog.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Coron Island Day: Twin Lagoon and Kayangan, Honestly',
        'slug' => 'coron-twin-lagoon-kayangan-honest-island-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Twin Lagoon and Kayangan Lake are the two stops every Coron itinerary builds around. Here is what they look like now, the climb at Kayangan, and what to bring.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Coron got loud in the late 2010s, then quieter through the pandemic, then loud again. The two stops that still anchor every boat itinerary are Kayangan Lake and Twin Lagoon, both on the Coron Island side of the bay. The day works if you accept that the climb at Kayangan is real and the kayak fee at Twin Lagoon is non-negotiable.</p><p>This is not the Coron of overwater bungalows. Coron Island itself is ancestral land of the Tagbanwa, and the lake and lagoon access is regulated by the community. The fees you pay at the entrance go back to maintenance and the indigenous council.</p><h2>Kayangan Lake</h2><p>Kayangan is the lake every Coron postcard uses. The boat docks at a small inlet, you pay the entrance fee, and you climb a steep wooden boardwalk up over the limestone ridge. The viewpoint on top is the famous Coron shot, the bay and the karst islands framed through the gap. From the viewpoint, you walk down to the lake itself.</p><h3>The Climb</h3><p>The climb is short but no joke if you came in slippers. Bring shoes with grip or proper aqua shoes. The path is a mix of wooden planks and worn limestone, and the descent on the lake side is slick when wet. Bring water, the climb is sunny.</p><h3>The Lake Itself</h3><p>Kayangan is freshwater, almost surreal in clarity, and the swim across to the small cave on the far side is one of those quiet moments worth the trip. Snorkeling gear is allowed but no fins, the rangers enforce this to protect the lake floor. There are no bathrooms inside, so plan accordingly before the climb.</p><h2>Twin Lagoon</h2><p>Twin Lagoon is the more dramatic of the two. The boat anchors at the outer lagoon and you reach the inner lagoon either by swimming under the low rock gap at low tide, or by climbing the wooden ladder over the limestone wall at high tide. Either way works, and the kayak rental is the cleaner option if you have a camera you want to keep dry.</p><h3>What Makes It Twin</h3><p>The inner lagoon water sits at a different temperature than the outer. Salt water on top, freshwater seeping in from below, and a halocline where the two meet that looks like a blurry layer when you swim through it. Snorkel the gap and you will see it.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Aqua shoes for the Kayangan climb</li><li>Cash in small bills for the multiple entrance fees</li><li>A dry bag for your phone and wallet</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, no sprays</li><li>A light rashguard for the boat ride and the lagoon swim</li><li>A reusable water bottle, refills at the boat</li></ul><h2>How to Book the Day</h2><p>The standard Coron tour is run out of Coron town in Busuanga, not Coron Island itself. Operators bundle Kayangan, Twin Lagoon, Skeleton Wreck, and one or two beach stops into a full-day boat with lunch. Book through your accommodation or the tourism office, both are reliable and the price difference is small.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>Direct flights from Manila land at Francisco Reyes Airport in Busuanga. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> and Philippine Airlines both run the route daily. The other way in is the long overnight ferry from Manila on <a href="https://travel.2go.com.ph" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">2GO Travel</a>, which takes around 14 hours and is the sulit option if you can sleep through the ride.</p><p>For places to stay in Coron town and the quieter side of Busuanga, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g664654-Coron_Busuanga_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Coron town is closer to the boats, Busuanga is quieter.</p><p>Coron rewards travelers who go early in the day and accept the fees as part of the deal. Kayangan and Twin Lagoon hold up, even on the second visit.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2017/08/puerto-princesa-palawan-travel-guide-itinerary-blog.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinoy Adventurista</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Coron Twin Lagoon and Kayangan Lake Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to the Coron island day. What Kayangan Lake and Twin Lagoon look like now, the climb, the fees, and what to bring for a smooth boat trip.',
        'tags' => 'Coron, Palawan, Kayangan, Twin Lagoon, island hopping',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'el-nido',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2018/04/port-barton-palawan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Poor Traveler',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Port Barton: The Slow Palawan Alternative to El Nido',
        'slug' => 'port-barton-slow-palawan-alternative-el-nido',
        'excerpt' => 'Port Barton is the quieter Palawan stop most travelers skip. The island hopping is slower, the beach town smaller, and the kwento richer if you give it three nights.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Port Barton is the Palawan town El Nido travelers find by accident. It sits halfway between Puerto Princesa and El Nido, on a calm bay with a single main street and a brownout schedule that still feels real. The boat tours go to the same general bay as El Nido but with a fraction of the crowds, and the village still feels like a fishing barangay first and a tourist stop second.</p><p>This is not the place to come for nightlife or shopping. This is the place to come when El Nido starts feeling like a queue. Tara, here is the read.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>The most reliable way to reach Port Barton is by van from either Puerto Princesa or El Nido. From Puerto Princesa, the ride is around three to four hours on the now-paved road. From El Nido, the trip is around two and a half hours. Vans leave on a fixed schedule and you book at any of the tour offices in town. The seats are cramped but the road is fine.</p><h3>Where to Get the Van</h3><p>In Puerto Princesa, the Recaro and Lexxus vans run the morning trip from the San Jose terminal. In El Nido, the same operators pick up at your guesthouse if you book the day before. There is no airport in Port Barton itself, which is the main reason the town stayed quiet.</p><h2>What to Do in Three Days</h2><p>Three nights is the right length. Two is rushed, four feels long unless you really want to disconnect.</p><h3>Day 1: Settle and Walk</h3><p>Arrive by lunch, drop your bags, then walk the single beach road. There are a handful of small restaurants serving grilled fish and pasta, a sari-sari store, and a few coconut shacks. Sit out the afternoon, swim off the beach, and watch the boats come back from the morning tours. Sunset is the main event in Port Barton.</p><h3>Day 2: Island Hopping Tour</h3><p>The standard tour visits a rotation of small islands and reefs in the bay. The most common stops include German Island, the Maxima sandbar, Exotic Island, and a snorkeling spot at a turtle sanctuary. Lunch is grilled on the beach. The boats are smaller than the El Nido fleet, so the day feels less rushed.</p><h3>Day 3: Land Tour or Slow Morning</h3><p>The land tour to Pamuayan Waterfall is a calm hike through the forest behind the village. Or skip it and take a longer morning at the beach, then catch the afternoon van out. Either is valid.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Cash in small bills, the one ATM in town has a habit of running out</li><li>A power bank, brownouts happen and the village generator runs on a schedule</li><li>A flashlight or headlamp for the walk home from dinner</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen and a hat</li><li>A book or a downloaded movie, the Wi-Fi is slow</li></ul><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>The accommodation in Port Barton is mostly small guesthouses and a few mid-range beachfront places. There are no big chain hotels. For comparing the smaller properties, you can check listings on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g3437527-Port_Barton_San_Vicente_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. The beachfront places fill up fast in dry season, so book ahead.</p><h2>Getting Out</h2><p>The afternoon vans to El Nido or Puerto Princesa leave around 1 p.m. and 4 p.m. If you are flying out the same day, plan a buffer night in Puerto Princesa because the van trips can run late. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> runs the most flights into Puerto Princesa.</p><p>Port Barton is the place you go when you want to remember why you started traveling in Palawan in the first place. Slow it down, eat the grilled tuna twice, and let the brownouts pass.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.thepoortraveler.net/2018/04/port-barton-palawan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Poor Traveler</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Port Barton Palawan: Slow Alternative to El Nido | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'Why Port Barton works as a calm three-night Palawan stop. Van routes from El Nido and Puerto Princesa, what to do, and what to bring.',
        'tags' => 'Port Barton, Palawan, slow travel, island hopping, DIY',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'el-nido',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://thepinaysolobackpacker.com/puerto-princesa-underground-river/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinay Solo Backpacker',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Puerto Princesa Underground River: A DIY Guide for First Timers',
        'slug' => 'puerto-princesa-underground-river-diy-first-timers',
        'excerpt' => 'The Underground River is still one of the country\'s most visited natural sites. Here is the DIY route, the permit process, and how to actually enjoy the cave instead of rushing through it.',
        'content_html' => '<p>The Puerto Princesa Subterranean River is a UNESCO World Heritage site and a New 7 Wonder of Nature, and it still holds up as a half-day trip if you plan around the permit system. The cave is around two hours from Puerto Princesa city by van, plus a short boat ride from Sabang Beach, plus the paddle-boat ride into the cave itself. The whole loop is doable in one long day, but the smart move is to stay overnight in Sabang.</p><p>This is the practical read for first-timers, with the DIY route and the permit notes.</p><h2>The Permit Is Mandatory</h2><p>The site limits visitors to 900 per day to protect the cave. You cannot just show up in Sabang. The permit has to be secured in advance, either through a registered tour operator in Puerto Princesa or at the Underground River booking office in the city. Walk-in slots exist but they sell out in peak season, especially December to May.</p><h3>Two Ways to Book</h3><p>The easier way is to book a tour package through any reputable agency along Rizal Avenue in Puerto Princesa. The package usually includes the permit, the van transfer, the boat fee, the buffet lunch, and the audio guide. The DIY way is to secure the permit at the office one to two days before, then ride a public van to Sabang and arrange the boat at the pier yourself.</p><h2>The Day Itself</h2><p>If you DIY from Puerto Princesa, leave by 6 a.m. The van ride to Sabang takes around two hours through the Palawan interior. At Sabang pier, present the permit, pay the boat fee, and queue for the outrigger to the cave entrance.</p><h3>Inside the Cave</h3><p>You ride a small paddle-boat into the cave with a guide. The standard route covers around 1.5 kilometers of the navigable river, past limestone formations the guides have named over the years, including the cathedral and the candle. The audio guide loops in three languages and you control the pace. The cave is dark, so the camera flash will not help unless you have proper low-light gear.</p><h3>What to Wear</h3><ul><li>Closed shoes with grip, the boardwalk to the cave entrance is wet</li><li>A light long-sleeve, the cave is cool and damp</li><li>A hat for the beach walk to and from the boat</li><li>Insect repellent for the monkeys at the entrance, they grab loose plastic</li><li>A dry bag for your phone, the boat can splash</li></ul><h2>Stay in Sabang If You Can</h2><p>The smart move is to stay one night in Sabang. You wake up early, catch the first boat to the cave when the morning light is best, and have the rest of the day for the mangrove paddle tour and the small beach. The Sabang Mangrove Paddle Boat Tour is a calm 45-minute ride through a tidal river with a local rower. It pairs naturally with the Underground River day.</p><h2>Getting to Puerto Princesa</h2><p>Direct flights from Manila and Cebu land at Puerto Princesa International. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> has the most slots. The city itself has good food along Rizal Avenue and the Baywalk area for sunset, so plan one or two nights in Puerto Princesa before or after the Underground River day.</p><p>For places to stay in Puerto Princesa city and in Sabang itself, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298447-Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Staying in the city is the easier base, staying in Sabang is the calmer one.</p><h2>One Tip Most Tours Skip</h2><p>Ask for the extended boat route inside the cave. The standard tour does not include it, but if your boat is light on passengers, the guide can sometimes extend the loop to the further chamber. This is the part with the larger formations and fewer photos.</p><p>The Underground River still earns the trip. Plan the permit, sleep in Sabang, and let the cave do the work.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://thepinaysolobackpacker.com/puerto-princesa-underground-river/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinay Solo Backpacker</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Puerto Princesa Underground River DIY Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm DIY guide to the Puerto Princesa Underground River. Permit process, van route, what to wear, and why staying in Sabang makes the trip easier.',
        'tags' => 'Puerto Princesa, Underground River, Palawan, UNESCO, DIY',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'el-nido',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2022/09/puerto-galera-beach-resorts-in-mindoro.html',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Pinoy Adventurista',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Puerto Galera White Beach: A Weekend Plan for Manila Travelers',
        'slug' => 'puerto-galera-white-beach-weekend-plan',
        'excerpt' => 'White Beach is the loudest of the three Puerto Galera beaches and the easiest weekend escape from Manila. Here is how to plan around the crowd and still enjoy the sand.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Puerto Galera has three main beaches and White Beach is the busiest of them. It is the strip with the bars, the karaoke, the banana boats, and the beachfront vendors selling shell anklets. The sand is genuinely white, the water is clean enough for a swim, and the sunset is the reason most weekenders keep coming back from Manila.</p><p>The trick to enjoying White Beach is to plan around its rhythm. Wake up early, swim before the day-tour boats arrive, eat lunch back from the strip, and stay out for the sunset that the day-trippers always miss.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>The route from Manila is a Cubao or Buendia bus to Batangas Pier, then the RORO ferry across to Muelle in Puerto Galera. The full trip runs around four to six hours depending on traffic at SLEX and the boat schedule.</p><h3>The Ferry</h3><p>Two main ferry types run the Batangas-to-Puerto-Galera route. The faster outrigger banca takes around one hour and lands directly at Muelle pier. The bigger RORO takes around two hours and lands at the same pier but with vehicle space. Check the latest schedule with the ferry operators at Batangas Pier, the timing shifts with the season. From Muelle, a jeepney or van takes you to White Beach in 20 minutes.</p><h2>What to Do at White Beach</h2><p>White Beach is the swim-and-eat beach. The water is shallow for a long way out, which makes it safe for kids and weak swimmers, and the sand is soft enough to walk on barefoot.</p><h3>Morning</h3><p>Wake up by 6 a.m. and walk the length of the beach before the day-trip boats arrive. The strip is at its calmest in the first two hours of light. Breakfast at one of the smaller cantinas behind the main row is cheaper and the food is honestly better than the beachfront pancakes.</p><h3>Afternoon</h3><p>The afternoon is for the water sports if that is your thing. Banana boat rides, parasailing, jet skis, and small island-hopping bancas all operate from the beach. The standard short banca trip covers Coral Garden and Haligi Beach. Negotiate the boat fee with the captain directly, not with the touts on the sand.</p><h3>Sunset</h3><p>White Beach faces west and the sunset is the consistent highlight. Find a beanbag at one of the calmer bars at the south end of the strip, order a cold drink, and watch the light go through the sailboats anchored off the beach.</p><h2>Where to Eat</h2><ul><li>Grilled tuna and pork barbecue at the small cantinas behind the strip</li><li>Sinigang and pancit at the Filipino restaurants in the village</li><li>Pizza and pasta at the western-leaning restaurants on the strip itself</li><li>Halo-halo at any of the dessert stalls past the village center</li></ul><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>White Beach has the most accommodation, from cheaper guesthouses behind the strip to larger beachfront properties. The strip is loud at night, so if you are a light sleeper, pick a place set back from the front row. For listings you can compare on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729739-Puerto_Galera_Oriental_Mindoro_Province_Mindoro-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. If you want quieter, look at Aninuan Beach next door instead of White Beach itself.</p><h2>One More Tip</h2><p>Bring cash. The card machines at the small shops are unreliable and the ATM near the village center can run out on long weekends. Bring more than you think you need.</p><p>White Beach is the right pick for a quick weekend from Manila if you go in with the right energy. Loud, friendly, sun-tired by 5 p.m., and home by Monday morning.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.pinoyadventurista.com/2022/09/puerto-galera-beach-resorts-in-mindoro.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Pinoy Adventurista</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Puerto Galera White Beach Weekend Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm weekend plan for Puerto Galera White Beach from Manila. Ferry routes, what to do, where to eat, and how to plan around the day-tour crowds.',
        'tags' => 'Puerto Galera, White Beach, Mindoro, weekend, Manila',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'puerto-galera',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://coffeeandcaminos.com/travel/30-days-in-the-philippines-calapan-minodoro/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Coffee and Caminos',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Calapan, Mindoro: A Budget Stop That Most Travelers Skip',
        'slug' => 'calapan-mindoro-budget-stop-travelers-skip',
        'excerpt' => 'Calapan is the working city on the Oriental Mindoro side that most Puerto Galera travelers skip. Here is why it deserves a night or two on a slow Mindoro loop.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Calapan is the capital of Oriental Mindoro and one of those Filipino cities that travelers rarely give time. Most Manila weekenders take the Batangas ferry straight to Puerto Galera and never see the eastern side of the island. That is a missed kwento. Calapan is the real working face of Mindoro, with a calm waterfront, a busy palengke, and access to the mangroves and the inland river towns.</p><p>This is not a beach destination. This is the budget stop you make when you want to slow down between the resort towns.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>The Batangas to Calapan RORO ferry is the main route. The crossing takes around two hours on the regular ferry. Vehicle slots are available for travelers driving in. From Manila, take a bus from Cubao or Buendia to Batangas Pier, then ride the ferry across. The full trip runs around four to five hours.</p><h3>From Other Mindoro Points</h3><p>If you are already in Puerto Galera, the jeepney from Sabang to Calapan takes around two hours through the mountain road. The ride is bumpy but scenic, with banana farms and pine sections at the higher elevation.</p><h2>What to Do in Calapan</h2><p>Calapan rewards travelers who walk. The downtown grid is small and most of the things worth seeing are within a tricycle ride of the cathedral.</p><h3>Silonay Mangrove Conservation Area</h3><p>Silonay is the standout reason to come to Calapan. The 42-hectare protected mangrove sits on the coast and you walk a long bamboo boardwalk through the canopy. There are migratory birds in the cooler months, fireflies at dusk, and kayak rentals for paddling through the inner channels. The entrance fee is small and goes back to the village.</p><h3>Calapan Cathedral and Plaza</h3><p>The Sto. Nino Cathedral fronts the central plaza. The cathedral itself is calm and the plaza is the local pasyalan spot at sunset. Walk the perimeter, sit on the benches, and watch the city wind down.</p><h3>The Public Market</h3><p>The Calapan Public Market is the kind of palengke that still feels like a working market, not a tourist setup. Buy bibingka, suman, and sweet local mangoes. The dried fish section has danggit and dilis from the small fishing communities along the coast.</p><h2>Where to Eat</h2><ul><li>Local carinderias near the cathedral for sinigang, kare-kare, and tapsilog</li><li>The bibingka stalls outside the market in the morning</li><li>Seafood at the small restaurants along the bayside road</li><li>Brewed Mindoro coffee at the cafes near the provincial capitol</li><li>Halo-halo at any of the dessert spots in the downtown grid</li></ul><h2>Side Trips From Calapan</h2><p>Calapan works as a base for the inland Oriental Mindoro towns. Naujan Lake, the largest lake in the province, is a 45-minute drive north and the surrounding villages still feel agricultural. Tamaraw Falls in Baco is a one-hour ride and a popular weekend stop for the locals. Pinagsabangan Beach on the way to Pola gives you a quieter coastline than the Puerto Galera strip.</p><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>Calapan accommodation is mostly small business hotels and pension houses, which suits the budget traveler. The pickings are not glamorous but they are clean and reliable. For listings you can compare on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298447-Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most properties are walking distance from the cathedral and the market.</p><h2>Getting Out</h2><p>The afternoon ferries back to Batangas leave hourly from Calapan Pier. If you are pushing south, the bus to San Jose in Occidental Mindoro takes around five to six hours over the central highway. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> also runs limited flights from Manila to San Jose if you want to skip the bus.</p><p>Calapan is the slow Mindoro stop. It rewards travelers who want to see the working city behind the resort beaches.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://coffeeandcaminos.com/travel/30-days-in-the-philippines-calapan-minodoro/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Coffee and Caminos</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Calapan Mindoro Budget Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to Calapan, the working city most Mindoro travelers skip. Ferry routes, Silonay mangroves, the public market, and where to eat.',
        'tags' => 'Calapan, Mindoro, budget, ferry, slow travel',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'puerto-galera',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.kingtolentino.com/blog/puerto-galera-travel-guide',
        'source_blog_name' => 'King Tolentino',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Sabang Beach, Puerto Galera: A Calm Read for Divers',
        'slug' => 'sabang-beach-puerto-galera-calm-read-divers',
        'excerpt' => 'Sabang is the dive side of Puerto Galera, with over 30 sites within a short boat ride and a small-town feel separate from White Beach. Here is the practical read.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Sabang sits at the northern end of the Puerto Galera peninsula and serves as the dive capital of the area. The bay is shallow at the entry and drops fast at the wreck sites, which is exactly the kind of profile beginner and advanced divers both want. The town itself is small, divided into three beach sections, and the rhythm follows the dive boats.</p><p>If you came to Puerto Galera to learn to dive or to log more bottom time, Sabang is the side you base out of. If you came to party on the beach, you are looking at White Beach instead.</p><h2>The Three Sabang Beaches</h2><p>The Sabang peninsula has three beaches and they each have a different feel.</p><h3>Sabang Beach</h3><p>The middle one. This is where the bars, the dive shops, and most of the restaurants sit. It is the loudest of the three after dark but still calm by White Beach standards. Easy walking distance to most of the dive operators.</p><h3>Small Lalaguna</h3><p>Where most of the dive resorts are based. Quieter than Sabang Beach itself, with a short walk along the rocky path to reach the bars and restaurants. This is the right pick if you want to be five steps from your dive shop.</p><h3>Big Lalaguna</h3><p>The far western beach, the quietest of the three. A few dive resorts, a couple of restaurants, and a calmer beach for the afternoon swim between dives. Good for divers who want to read between sessions.</p><h2>The Dive Sites</h2><p>There are over 30 dive sites in the Puerto Galera area. The fast boats from Sabang reach most of them in 10 to 20 minutes.</p><h3>Canyons</h3><p>The signature dive. A drift dive through three deep limestone canyons, swept by a current that brings in trevallies, batfish, and the occasional manta ray during the right months. Advanced divers only, you need to be comfortable with current.</p><h3>Alma Jane Wreck</h3><p>A large wreck around 30 meters deep just outside Sabang. Sits upright, accessible to advanced open water divers, and home to schooling batfish and giant frogfish. Night dives here are popular for the muck-diving crowd.</p><h3>Shallow Sites for Beginners</h3><p>Coral Garden, Sabang Wrecks (the smaller shallow wrecks), and Monkey Beach Reef are the standard beginner sites. Calm currents, good visibility most of the year, and easy reef teaching environments.</p><h2>When to Go</h2><p>The best diving runs from October to March, which lines up with the dry season. Visibility peaks at 20 to 30 meters in the cooler months. Diving continues year-round but the summer water can get warmer and visibility drops with the occasional rain runoff.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Your dive logbook and certification card</li><li>A surface marker buoy if you have one</li><li>A small flashlight for the wreck dives and night dives</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen for the surface intervals</li><li>Sea sickness tablets if you are sensitive to the boat ride</li><li>A waterproof watch or dive computer</li></ul><h2>Getting There</h2><p>Same route as White Beach. Manila to Batangas Pier by bus, then the ferry across to Muelle in Puerto Galera. From Muelle, a tricycle or jeepney takes you to Sabang in around 30 minutes through the mountain road.</p><p>The fast outrigger ferry from Batangas takes about an hour. The slower RORO takes about two. Check the schedule at the ferry counter, the timing shifts seasonally.</p><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>Sabang has the most dive resorts of any Puerto Galera area. Most operators bundle accommodation with their dive packages, which is the sulit option if you plan to dive every day. For listings you can compare on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g729739-Puerto_Galera_Oriental_Mindoro_Province_Mindoro-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Big Lalaguna is the right pick for quieter nights.</p><h2>Travel Logistics</h2><p>If you are flying in from Cebu or Davao, <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> runs the most flights to Manila with quick connections to the Batangas bus terminals.</p><p>Sabang holds up as the dive side. Calm bars at night, three solid dives a day, and the kwento with the dive crew that lasts the trip.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.kingtolentino.com/blog/puerto-galera-travel-guide" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">King Tolentino</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Sabang Beach Puerto Galera Dive Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to Sabang, the dive side of Puerto Galera. The three beaches, the wreck and canyon sites, when to go, and how to plan a diving stay.',
        'tags' => 'Sabang, Puerto Galera, diving, Mindoro, wreck dive',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'puerto-galera',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://thequeensescape.com/apo-reef-natural-park-in-sablayan-mindoro-occidental-travel-guide/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'The Queen\'s Escape',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Apo Reef, Mindoro: Diving the Second Largest Atoll in the World',
        'slug' => 'apo-reef-mindoro-diving-second-largest-atoll',
        'excerpt' => 'Apo Reef in Sablayan is the second largest contiguous reef system in the world. Here is the calm read on how to get there and what the dive trips look like.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Apo Reef sits around 30 kilometers off the western coast of Occidental Mindoro, in the middle of the Mindoro Strait. It is the largest atoll-type reef system in the Philippines and the second largest contiguous reef in the world, after the Great Barrier Reef. The reef hosts around 400 species of coral and 385 species of fish, including reef sharks, manta rays, and the occasional whale shark in the right season.</p><p>This is not a casual day trip. Reaching Apo Reef takes a flight, a bus ride, and a boat. The reward is reef diving on the cleanest big-fish site in the country.</p><h2>Getting There</h2><p>The standard route is to fly from Manila to San Jose in Occidental Mindoro on <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a>. From San Jose, a bus to Sablayan takes around three hours. Sablayan is the jump-off port for Apo Reef. From the Sablayan pier, the boat to Apo Reef takes another two to three hours through the strait.</p><h3>The Longer Land Route</h3><p>You can also go overland from Manila by RORO through Calapan, then by bus across the central highway to San Jose. The trip takes a full day but it is the sulit option if you have time and want to see the Mindoro interior.</p><h2>Where to Base</h2><p>You have three reasonable bases for an Apo Reef trip.</p><h3>Sablayan Town</h3><p>The mainland town with the most accommodation options and the most reliable boat connections. Best if you want to combine the reef trip with the Sablayan Prison and Penal Farm Eco-Tourism Park, which is a calm jungle trek on the mainland.</p><h3>North Pandan Island</h3><p>A small island a short boat ride from Sablayan with its own resort. The base most divers prefer because the morning boat to Apo Reef is shorter from here. Quiet, no nightlife, just diving and reading on the beach.</p><h3>Apo Reef Itself</h3><p>The reef has a ranger station and limited camping on the main island. This is the move for the truly committed. Bring your own food and water, and book the camping permit through the Sablayan tourism office in advance.</p><h2>The Diving</h2><p>Apo Reef is a wall and drift dive site. The visibility is consistently 20 to 30 meters in the right season. Reef sharks, sea turtles, and big schools of jacks are the regular sightings. The deeper sites at the outer wall bring in pelagics, including the occasional manta during the right months.</p><h3>Recommended Sites</h3><ul><li>Apo Reef Lighthouse drop-off for the wall dive</li><li>Shark Ridge for the white tip and black tip reef sharks</li><li>Hunter\'s Rock for the schooling pelagics</li><li>Binangaan Drop-off for the soft coral garden</li><li>Pandan Reef for the easier checkout dive</li></ul><h2>When to Go</h2><p>The dive season runs from November to May. Conditions are best from March to May when the sea is calm and visibility peaks. Avoid the southwest monsoon months from June to October when the boat crossings get rough and many operators close the route.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Full dive certification cards, advanced open water minimum</li><li>Your own dive computer, the resort rentals are limited</li><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the reef rangers are strict</li><li>Cash for the marine park fee, payable at the ranger station</li><li>Sea sickness tablets, the strait crossing can be rough</li><li>A surface marker buoy and whistle for safety</li></ul><h2>Where to Stay</h2><p>Sablayan and North Pandan Island are the realistic options. The accommodation in Sablayan is mostly small business hotels and pension houses. North Pandan has the one main resort with bundled dive packages. For listings around Sablayan and the wider Occidental Mindoro area, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g1819247-Sablayan_Occidental_Mindoro_Province_Mindoro-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>.</p><h2>One More Note</h2><p>Apo Reef is a marine protected area. The rangers enforce the rules. No fishing, no fin contact with coral, no plastic on the boat, and the visitor count is capped daily. Respect the cap and the reef will keep working.</p><p>Apo Reef is the long trip that pays off. Plan for the travel, dive the wall, and the reef will out-do every other Philippine dive site on your logbook.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://thequeensescape.com/apo-reef-natural-park-in-sablayan-mindoro-occidental-travel-guide/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">The Queen\'s Escape</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Apo Reef Mindoro Diving Guide | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to diving Apo Reef in Sablayan, Occidental Mindoro. How to get there, where to base, dive sites, and when to go.',
        'tags' => 'Apo Reef, Mindoro, Sablayan, diving, marine park',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'puerto-galera',
    ],
    [
        'source_url' => 'https://www.taraletsanywhere.com/island-hopping-honda-bay-palawan/',
        'source_blog_name' => 'Tara Lets Anywhere',
        'source_image_url' => null,
        'title' => 'Honda Bay Island Hopping: The Calm Puerto Princesa Day',
        'slug' => 'honda-bay-island-hopping-calm-puerto-princesa-day',
        'excerpt' => 'Honda Bay is the easy island hopping day in Puerto Princesa, with three to four small islands and shallow snorkeling within a 45-minute drive of the city.',
        'content_html' => '<p>Honda Bay is the island hopping day every Puerto Princesa itinerary defaults to. The bay sits around 45 minutes north of the city, and the usual loop covers three or four small islands with shallow reefs, white sand stretches, and a buffet lunch on one of the bigger islands. It is not the dramatic limestone scenery of El Nido, but it earns its place as the calmer Palawan beach day.</p><p>This is the read for travelers who want a half-day at the water without committing to the longer El Nido or Coron trips.</p><h2>The Islands</h2><p>Tour operators rotate stops based on the day, but the standard rotation pulls from five or six islands in the bay.</p><h3>Luli Island</h3><p>Luli stands for lulubog-lilitaw, the Tagalog phrase for sinks-and-rises, because the island disappears at high tide and reappears at low tide. The sandbar at low tide is the photo most travelers come for. Snorkeling around the sandbar edges is shallow and easy.</p><h3>Cowrie Island</h3><p>The biggest of the regular stops. Cowrie has cottages, a buffet restaurant, parasailing, jet skis, and a small dive shop. This is the lunch stop on most tour rotations. Walk past the cottages for a quieter stretch of beach on the far side.</p><h3>Starfish Island</h3><p>Named for the starfish you used to see in the shallows. The numbers have dropped from the early 2010s when every tourist held them up for photos, but the island still has a clean beach and shallow reef snorkeling. Do not pick up the starfish, the rangers will call you out.</p><h3>Pandan Island</h3><p>Smaller and quieter, with the best snorkeling reef of the standard stops. Some boats add this in place of Cowrie if the lunch buffet is included separately.</p><h2>How to Book</h2><p>You can book through any of the agencies along Rizal Avenue in Puerto Princesa, through your accommodation, or directly at the Honda Bay port in Sta. Lourdes. The package usually includes the boat, the island fees, the buffet lunch, and the snorkeling gear.</p><h3>Joining or Chartering</h3><p>Joining a shared boat is the cheaper option and you meet other travelers. Chartering a private boat for a group of four to six is the sulit move if you want flexibility on the stops and the timing.</p><h2>What to Bring</h2><ul><li>Reef-safe sunscreen, the rangers check at the port</li><li>Aqua shoes for the rocky beach landings</li><li>A dry bag for your phone and cash</li><li>A rashguard for the shallow snorkel sessions</li><li>A hat and sunglasses for the boat ride between stops</li><li>Cash for the additional island fees not always covered by the tour</li></ul><h2>The Day Itself</h2><p>Boats leave the Honda Bay port between 8 and 9 a.m. You spend around an hour at each stop, with the lunch stop running closer to two hours. The whole tour wraps by around 3 p.m. and you are back at your Puerto Princesa hotel by 4 p.m.</p><h3>Pair It With Iwahig Firefly Watching</h3><p>The smart Puerto Princesa day pairs Honda Bay in the morning with the Iwahig Firefly Watching tour at night. You eat dinner along the river, then ride a paddle boat up the dark mangrove channel where the fireflies cluster on the trees. It is the calm closing kwento to a sun-tired day.</p><h2>Getting to Puerto Princesa</h2><p>Direct flights from Manila, Cebu, and Davao land at Puerto Princesa International Airport. <a href="https://www.cebupacificair.com" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Cebu Pacific</a> has the most slots. From the airport, a tricycle or van takes you to the city center in about 20 minutes.</p><p>For places to stay in Puerto Princesa city, you can compare options on <a href="https://www.tripadvisor.com.ph/Hotels-g298447-Palawan_Island_Palawan_Province_Mimaropa-Hotels.html" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">TripAdvisor PH</a>. Most properties cluster along Rizal Avenue and the Baywalk area.</p><h2>One Note on Crowds</h2><p>Honda Bay gets crowded on weekends and on the Christmas and Holy Week peaks. Go on a weekday if you can, and ask your operator to start at the further islands first so you stay ahead of the main fleet.</p><p>Honda Bay holds up as the calm Palawan day. Three or four islands, shallow snorkeling, and a buffet lunch on the sand. Worth pairing with the Underground River for a complete Puerto Princesa visit.</p><p class="source-credit"><em>Inspired by and adapted from <a href="https://www.taraletsanywhere.com/island-hopping-honda-bay-palawan/" target="_blank" rel="noopener nofollow">Tara Lets Anywhere</a>.</em></p>',
        'meta_title' => 'Honda Bay Island Hopping Guide Palawan | Resort Guru PH',
        'meta_description' => 'A calm guide to Honda Bay island hopping in Puerto Princesa. The five regular islands, how to book, what to bring, and how to pair the trip with fireflies.',
        'tags' => 'Honda Bay, Puerto Princesa, Palawan, island hopping, snorkeling',
        'cover_destination_key' => 'el-nido',
    ],

